<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-06-05T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-06-05T16:00:00-05:00" n="66" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d66">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/2586</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">Page</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-06-05T22:00:00+01:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 5, 1917, 10 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>6368. Your 4916, June 4, 3 p.m. Lord Robert Cecil must have a conference
                            before can give a formal or final answer which he promises forthwith.
                            His personal views are favorable to a joint representation but he
                            considers China’s entry into war although secondary to domestic unity
                            and peace of very great importance. China’s entry would deal a hard blow
                            to Germany in trade relations after the war and he regards German fear
                            of complete commercial isolation as one of the strongest kinds of
                            pressure to bring peace.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
